description.p:
According to one embodiment of the invention a single pivot is fixed relative to the bicycle; wherein

the first brake arm and the second brake arms are pivotally disposed on the pivot, wherein each brake arm respectively including a brake arm point;

a ground body is disposed on the pivot and releasably securable thereto, wherein the ground body including a link pivot;

a link member pivotally is disposed on the link pivot, wherein the link member has a first end contacting the first brake arm and a second end contacting the second brake arm and is arranged so as to synchronize the motion of the first brake arm and the second brake arm; and wherein

a spring biasing the first and second brake arms into a rest position.

claim.claim-text:
A brake assembly for a bicycle, comprising:
a first brake arm and a second brake arm pivotally disposed on a single pivot;

a ground body disposed on the pivot and releasably securable thereto, the ground body including a link pivot;
a link member pivotally disposed on the link pivot, the link member having a first end contacting the first brake arm and a second end contacting the second brake arm and arranged so as to synchronize the motion of the first brake arm and the second brake arm; and
a spring bearing against one or both of the first and second brake arms and biasing the first and second brake arms into a rest position.

The hydraulic rim brake assembly of claim 5, further including a single pivot fixed relative to the bicycle;

the first brake arm and the second brake arms pivotally disposed on the pivot, each brake arm respectively including a brake arm point;

a ground body disposed on the pivot and releasably securable thereto, the ground body including a link pivot;

a link member pivotally disposed on the link pivot, the link member having a first end contacting the first brake arm and a second end contacting the second brake arm and arranged so as to synchronize the motion of the first brake arm and the second brake arm; and

a spring biasing the first and second brake arms into a rest position.

A brake assembly for a bicycle, comprising:
a first brake arm and a second brake arm pivotally disposed on a single pivot;
an adjustable ground body disposed on the pivot and releasably securable thereto in a plurality of positions, the ground body including a link pivot;
a synchronous link mechanism including a link member pivotally disposed on the link pivot and interconnecting the ground body and the first and second brake arms and arranged so as to synchronize the motion of the first and second brake arms; and
a spring biasing the first and second brake arms into a rest position.
